    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I got a bit carried away with the goblin analogy. Let me break it down for you in a more straightforward way.\n\nThe escrow agent, also known as the escrow company, plays a crucial role in the home buying process. Their primary responsibility is to hold and manage the earnest money deposit, which is typically 1-3% of the purchase price.\n\nThe escrow agent is usually an independent third party, not affiliated with either the buyer or the seller. Their role is to ensure that the transaction is completed according to the terms of the sale agreement. They hold the earnest money in a separate account, separate from the closing funds, until the sale is complete.\n\nWhen the sale is finalized, the escrow agent releases the earnest money to the buyer, and the closing funds are disbursed to the seller. The escrow agent also handles other tasks, such as:\n\n* Reviewing and processing documents\n* Coordinating with the title company to ensure the property is transferred to the buyer's name\n* Managing the payment of real estate taxes and other closing costs\n\nIn essence, the escrow agent acts as a neutral intermediary, ensuring that the transaction is completed smoothly and according to the agreed-upon terms.",
